# Cairn — Master Execution Plan

> **This document is the single source of truth for what to build, in what order, and how.**
> Every task has: a goal, file-level instructions, layer coverage, gate checklists, SDE compliance checks, **and a mandatory learning phase.**
> This plan is designed so that ANY model (Gemini, Claude, or human) can pick up a task and execute it without ambiguity.
> **The learner (Akshat) must understand every concept deeply before code is written. Building without understanding is forbidden.**

---

## Restructured Gate System

### PRE-GATE (Before Starting Any Task)

The executor MUST output the following block and receive explicit user approval before writing any code:

```
=== PRE-GATE: [Task ID] ===
Task         : [one-line description]
Goal         : [what this task achieves]
Files        : [list of files to create/modify]
Layers       : [which of the 13 layers this touches]
Dependencies : [which tasks must be complete first]
Assumptions  : [any assumptions — user must confirm or deny each]
SDE Standards: [which of the 10 standards apply to this task]
================================
```

User responds: **"PRE-GATE approved. Proceed."** or asks questions.

### LEARN Phase (Between PRE-GATE and EXECUTION — MANDATORY)

Before writing a single line of code, the executor MUST teach the learner the core concepts of the task. This is NOT optional. This is NOT a quick summary. This follows the **Teaching Protocol** (Section 15 below).

**Flow:**
1. Identify the **Concepts to Master** listed in the task
2. For EACH concept, follow the 9-stage teaching flow (diagnose → frame → baseline → insight → mechanics → example → edge cases → tradeoffs → verify)
3. The learner must demonstrate understanding by answering questions and explaining the concept back
4. Only after the learner passes the understanding check does coding begin
5. If using Gemini for execution: Gemini must FIRST output a `=== CONCEPT BRIEF ===` block explaining what it's about to build and WHY, written as if teaching the learner. The learner reviews this before code is written.

```
=== CONCEPT BRIEF: [Task ID] ===
Concepts     : [list of concepts this task uses]
Why It Matters: [why this concept exists, what problem it solves]
How It Works  : [mechanics — step by step, not just "it does X"]
Key Insight   : [the non-obvious thing that makes this work]
Tradeoffs     : [what we gain, what we lose, alternatives considered]
Edge Cases    : [what could go wrong, how we handle it]
================================
```

The learner reviews the brief, asks questions if confused, and says **"Concept understood. Proceed to code."**

### EXECUTION Rules

1. Follow the file-level instructions in this plan exactly
2. Every new Java class gets: Javadoc, WHY comments, SLF4J logger
3. Every service method that's a public API gets: `@Audited` (once AOP is built), input validation
4. Every new REST endpoint gets: DTO input/output, `@Valid`, proper HTTP status codes, pagination where applicable
5. Run `mvn spotless:apply` before committing
6. Run `mvn verify` — all tests must pass
7. No code is committed without a test
8. While writing code, explain non-obvious decisions with inline `// WHY:` comments

### POST-GATE (Before Marking Complete)

The executor MUST output the following block and receive explicit user approval:

```
=== POST-GATE: [Task ID] ===
Files Created  : [list with paths]
Files Modified : [list with paths]
Tests Added    : [list with names and what they verify]
Tests Passing  : [X/X all green]
SDE Compliance : [checklist of which standards were applied]
Layer Coverage : [which layers were addressed]
Build Status   : mvn verify ✅
Spotless       : applied ✅
================================
```

User responds: **"POST-GATE approved."**

Then:
1. `git checkout -b feat/[task-id]`
2. `git add . && git commit -m "[Task ID]: [description]"`
3. `git push origin feat/[task-id]`
4. CI passes on GitHub Actions
5. `git checkout main && git merge feat/[task-id] && git push origin main`
6. Update `task.md` — mark task ✅
7. Update `PROJECT_JOURNAL.md` — add session entry

